#Text=Abraham van der Doort
#Text=Portrait of Abraham van der Doort , by William Dobson .
#Text=Abraham van der Doort ( c. 1575/1580 ? - June 1640 ) was a Dutch artist .
#Text=As Keeper of Charles I 's art collections , he was the first Surveyor of the King 's Pictures .
#Text=Van der Doort 's careworn face is familiar from a portrait and engravings held by the National Portrait Gallery in London , [ 1 ]
#Text=but little is known of his early life :
#Text=indeed , his date of birth is not known with any certainty .
#Text=He was probably the son of Peter van Do[o]rt , an engraver of Dutch descent who was working in Hamburg in the early years of the 17th century , [ 2 ]
#Text=a member of a family of Dutch craftsmen that also specialised in the design and manufacture of coins and medals .
#Text=Abraham van der Doort probably came to England around 1609 , a few years after James I became King of England .
#Text=Van der Doort came into the service of Charles ' elder brother , Prince Henry .

#Text=After Henry 's early death in 1612 , his collection of paintings , medals , coins and other objets d'art was inherited by Charles , and van der Doort accompanied the collection into Charles ' service .
#Text=After Charles succeeded his father as king in 1625 , van der Doort became Charles ' Groom of the Chamber , Surveyor of the King 's Pictures ; he designed new coins for the Royal Mint .
#Text=About 1639 , van der Doort compiled a manuscript catalogue of the art collection of the King , described by Ellis Waterhouse as " the fullest catalogues of their day in Europe . " [ 3 ]

#Text=The catalogue survives in a complete manuscript that was preserved by Elias Ashmole and is now held by the Bodleian Library , and in three fair copies of sections , all covered with van der Doort 's annotations in a tight crabbed hand .

#Text=Under van der Doort 's care , and with the guidance of painter-dealers , painter-ambassadors and English painting virtuosi , Charles had assembled what Oliver Millar , in editing a modern edition of catalogue , reckoned was the best single English collection of paintings ever made . [ 4 ]

#Text=George Vertue 's notes on the former Royal Collection were published in 1757 , which is the reason that , following its long series of the Vertue notebooks , a collated edition of the four manuscript catalogues was published by the Walpole Society as its Volume 37 ( 1958 – 60 ) ; it was edited by Millar , who later followed van der Doort as Surveyor of the Queen 's Pictures .

#Text=Millar provides the best biography of van der Doort , and details of the provenance of the pictures , many of which had come from the Gonzaga inheritance in Mantua , with a commentary on their later history and their attributions .
#Text=Van der Doort committed suicide in the summer of 1640 , distraught that he may have misplaced one of his master 's miniatures .
#Text=Charles ' collection was broken up and sold by auction in 1649 , after Charles had been executed .
#Text=Van der Doort never lost the Dutch accent that is preserved in his copious annotations to the catalogues in his entirely phonetic spelling .
